Causal Inference - Exercise RD

Michael Knaus

SoSe 25

These are the goals of today:

  • Run a Sharp RD analysis manually and using the rdrobust package

  • Run a Fuzzy RD analysis replicating Huh and Reif (2021)

Load and prepare election data

This dataset contains information on elections for the U.S. Senate during the period 1914–2010. We focus on the RD effect of the Democratic party winning a U.S. Senate seat on the vote share in the following election for that same seat. The data set contains these two variables that are relevant for us:

  • vote records the state-level vote share of the Democratic party in a given statewide election for a Senate seat (our \(Y\))

  • margin records the margin of victory of the Democratic party in the previous election for the same Senate seat (our \(X\))

url = "https://raw.githubusercontent.com/rdpackages/rdrobust/master/R/rdrobust_senate.csv"
data = read.csv(url)
head(data)

Define variables, in particular the treatment variable \(W = 1[margin > 0]\) and collect the crucial variables into a tibble for later use:

Y = data$vote
X = data$margin
c = 0
W = as.factor((X > c) * 1)
xyw = tibble(X,Y,W)

Run the local mean comparison for a grid of values (start with h = 0.5) and plot point estimates and confidence intervals along the grid.

h_seq = seq(0.5,100,0.5)
results_mat = matrix(rep(NA), nrow=length(h_seq), ncol = 2) #two columns: tau and s.e.

for (i in 1:length(h_seq)) {
  results_mat[i,1] = lm_robust(Y ~ W, subset = (X > c-h_seq[i] & X < h_seq[i]+c))$coefficients[2]
  results_mat[i,2] = lm_robust(Y ~ W, subset = (X > c-h_seq[i] & X < h_seq[i]+c))$std.error[2]
}

# Collect results: 
tau = results_mat[,1]
se = results_mat[,2]

CI_lower = results_mat[,1]-1.96*results_mat[,2]

Global OLS allowing for different slopes on each side

Package implementation

The package rdrobust (available for Python, R and Stata) is (to the best of my knowledge) the best maintained technology for RD analyses. It automates the optimal bandwidth search and comes with a lot of useful features (see their homepage).

It implements state-of-the-art bias correction and robust inference we have not the time to talk about but you should use if you had a real application:

Fuzzy RD

Teenage Driving and Mortality (Huh and Reif, 2021)

Teenage car accidents are responsible for over 60 percent of accidental deaths among adolescents—almost as common as suicides. Sifting through the causal relationship might be difficult, though: Teenagers who get their licenses right away might be different from those who wait. Perhaps the former are more risk-taking in general.

The paper we replicate looks closely at teenage driving and tries to figure out if getting a license actually causes an uptick in mortality and other risky behaviors.

We focus on the minimum driving age (MDA). The running variable, agemo_mda, is already centered and stands for the months before the MDA (our \(X\)).

There are two separate data sets we’ll be using:

  1. National Vital Statistics (1983–2014) is based on death certificate records and includes information on month and year of death, cause of death, and state of residence of a person.

    Mortality is measured retrospectively, so deaths at different ages are recorded as they occur. The authors then combine these counts with population estimates to get age-specific mortality rate per 100,000 person-years, cod_any (our \(Y\)).

  2. The driving behaviors (e.g., miles driven per week) are measured using a nationally representative sample of 20.000 students surveyed in 1995–1996. Same individuals were surveyed multiple times, so some of them aged across the threshold (before and after reaching driving age) and contributed to both sides.

    Our treatment variable \(W\) is DriverLicence, a share of sample with driving licence.

# Load Adult Health data for teens behaviour 
add_health = read_dta("https://julianreif.com/driving/data/add_health/derived/all.dta") %>%
  mutate(firstmonth = agemo_mda==0) # indicator: 1st month eligible to drive

# Load mortality data
df = read_dta("https://julianreif.com/driving/data/mortality/derived/all.dta") %>%
  mutate(firstmonth = agemo_mda==0,               # indicator: 1st month eligible to drive
         across(2:14, ~ . * 100000 / (pop / 12))) # deaths --> death rates

We wouldn’t expect any bunching here, since people cannot strategically alter their age to fall just above the cutoff:

ggplot(df, aes(x = agemo_mda, weight = pop)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 5, color = "black", fill = "skyblue") +
  labs(title = "Distribution of the Running Variable", x = "Months until Allowed to Drive", y = "Frequency") +
  theme_minimal() + geom_vline(xintercept = 0, color = "#E41A1C") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(size = 16, hjust = 0.5),
        axis.title = element_text(size = 14),
        panel.grid = element_line(color = "gray", linetype = "dotted", size = 0.5))

There is also no risk of sample selection because we observe the universe of deaths.

To identify the treatment effect, we need to make sure that the necessary assumptions hold.

First, the potential mortality rates \(Y(0), Y(1)\) must be continuous functions of age at the MDA threshold:

\[ \begin{align*} \lim_{x \to c} \mathbb{E}[Y(0) \, | \, X = x] &= \mathbb{E}[Y(0) \, | \, X = c] \\\ lim_{x \to c} \mathbb{E}[Y(1) \, | \, X = x] &= \mathbb{E}[Y(1) \, | \, X = c] \end{align*} \]

A teenager’s physical coordination, risk assessment abilities, and decision-making likely evolve smoothly around MDA.

Another assumption is monotonicity: the probability of receiving the treatment changes in a non-decreasing way:\[ \begin{equation*} \lim_{x \downarrow c} \mathbb{E}[W \, | \, X = x] \geq \lim_{x \uparrow c} \mathbb{E}[W \, | \, X = x], \end{equation*} \]

There basically should be no teens who would get licenses when not eligible but wouldn’t when eligible. This seems sensible: legal incentives are aligned with compliance.

First Stage Discontinuity: There must be a meaningful jump in the probability of having a driver’s license at the MDA threshold. We’ll check that empirically in a moment.

The most challenging in our context is the exclusion restriction. It requires that crossing the minimum driving age (MDA) threshold affects mortality rates (\(Y\)) only through obtaining a driver’s license (\(W\)). In other words, reaching the minimum driving age should not affect teenage mortality through any channel other than the increased likelihood of having a driver’s license.

Several mechanisms might be at play here. For example, teens may get rides from newly licensed friends, or parents may become less restrictive once teens are legally eligible to drive, even for those who do not immediately get a license. This, in turn, leads them to participate in potentially risky activities.

If we think this setting is credible enough, the Conditional LATE (CLATE) at the cutoff can be identified as

\[ \tau_{\text{LATE}} :=\mathbb{E}[Y(1)−Y(0)|T=c,X=c] = \dfrac{\lim_{X \downarrow C} \mathbb{E}\big[Y\mid X = x\big]-\lim_{X \uparrow c} \mathbb{E}\big[Y\mid X=x\big]}{\lim_{X \downarrow c} \mathbb{E}\big[W\mid X=x\big]-\lim_{X \uparrow c} \mathbb{E}\big[W\mid X=x\big]} \]

And estimated in a familiar way.

An intuitively appealing bandwidth to start with could be 12 months. It is not far-fetched to assume that teenagers within a year of becoming eligible to drive are comparable. We can then see how far the MSE-optimal bandwidth is from our guess.

We also add an additional control variable: \(C = \mathbf{1}[X=0]\). With monthly data, it is unclear whether someone who died in \(X=0\) did so before or after actually becoming eligible to drive. Including the dummy accounts for this measurement uncertainty at the cutoff.

Start by checking how many people actually do get a licence:

bandwidth = 12

# Subset data within bandwidth h = 12
temp_df = add_health[abs(add_health$agemo_mda) <= bandwidth, ]

W = temp_df$DriverLicense
X = temp_df$agemo_mda
C = as.integer(temp_df$firstmonth)

# Fit separate regressions for left and right of the cutoff
lm_left  = lm(W ~ X + C, subset = X < 0)
lm_right = lm(W ~ X + C, subset = X >= 0)

firstStage = coef(lm_right)[1] - coef(lm_left)[1]

Comparing the estimates:

print(rbind("CLATE Estimate (h=12)" = reducedForm / firstStage, 
      "CLATE Estimate (optimal h)"  = reducedFormMSE$Estimate[1] / firstStageMSE$Estimate[1]))
                           (Intercept)
CLATE Estimate (h=12)         35.02643
CLATE Estimate (optimal h)    31.39891

What is the interpretation of this local effect?

Scaling the all-cause mortality estimate by the driver’s license estimate suggests that driving increases total mortality at the cutoff by 31.4 deaths per 100,000 (81 percent) among teenagers who get a license.

With this result in hand, what kind of policy recommendation can we suggest?

It’s not obvious. For example, raising the MDA could reduce the effect of eligibility on mortality if older teenagers are more careful drivers. On the other hand, it could increase the effect if older teenagers are more likely to drink and drive.

Can we interpret our findings as causal? The most common MDA during our sample period is 16, which brings up the possibility that the results are driven by a “birthday effect” or another regulation that takes effect at age 16, such as the federal minimum legal working age or a state’s minimum school-leaving age.

The first concern is ruled out because the discontinuities we observe are long-lasting. For the second one, we can check for discontinuities in the probability of working or leaving school at the MDA cutoff:

X = add_health$agemo_mda
C = as.integer(add_health$firstmonth)

# Not enrolled nor graduated
Y1  = add_health$Work4weeks
RD1 = rdrobust(Y1, X, covs = C)

# Not enrolled nor graduated
Y2  = add_health$NotEnrolled
RD2 = rdrobust(Y2, X, covs = C)

rdplot(Y1, X, c = 0, p = 1, binselect = "esmv", kernel = "triangular",
       h = c(RD1$bws[1,1], RD1$bws[1,2]), title = "Work during last 4 weeks",
       subset=-RD1$bws[1,1]<= X & X <= RD1$bws[1,2],
       x.label = "Age in month relative to MDA", y.label = "Share Working")


rdplot(Y2, X, c = 0, p = 1, binselect = "esmv", kernel = "triangular",
       h = c(RD2$bws[1,1], RD2$bws[1,2]), title = "Not enrolled nor graduated",
       subset=-RD2$bws[1,1]<= X & X <= RD2$bws[1,2],
       x.label = "Age in month relative to MDA", y.label = "Share Not Enrolled")

(optional self-study)

  1. Following the earlier analysis, we can study how sensitive the results are to the choice of bandwidth. Examine how the bandwidth selection impacts the estimates. You can use the graph from before by creating a handy, reusable function.
  2. There are other causes of death in the dataset. The paper finds an unexpected result: female teenagers substitute away from firearms and toward drugs and gas poisoning when they gain access to a car. You can replicate this finding by doing a subgroup analysis.
  3. It is common practice to estimate the model using placebo cutoffs. You can do this and check whether the estimates are centered around zero.
